pred_data |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = log_followers, 
             y = .resid)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.4) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(subtitle = "Residual Plot from log_viewers vs log_followers", 
       title = "Residual Plot", 
       x = "log(followers)", 
       y = "Residuals", 
       caption = "Source: twitch_data")

I see a residual plot that shows the distance from each point to the linear model that was shown on the previous graph. As expected because our linear model is a good fit, most residuals center around 0 because there is little difference on average between each point and the line. However, there are a few big outliers with a residual over 1.5 or below -1. However these big residuals do not happen often in a particular range of log_followers so the linear model is a solid fit for this data and predicts the average viewers (log_viewers) well for the entire range of our x-variable (log_followers).

After fitting the model, I can assess the different coefficients for each language to see how many more/less average viewers there are in a particular language compared to English. The coefficients vary from -4085.8 to 5112.8 average viewers, with more negative coefficients than positive ones, which makes sense because we can expect most languages to have less average viewers than English. Because the standard deviation of average viewers is roughly 8500 average viewers (as calculated above), these coefficients are relatively small in size (less than one standard deviation in the raw data), which is a sign that the fitted model is an accurate prediction from what we know so far.

The 3 languages that have more average viewers than English are Spanish, Russian, and Arabic. Spanishâs coefficient is 1337 so they have an average viewership of 1337 + 5113 = 6450, since English has 5113 average viewers as the baseline. Similarly, Russian has a coefficient of 1481 and an average viewership of 1481 + 5113 = 6594, and Arabic has a coefficient of 569 and an average viewership of 569 + 5113 = 5682.
